1
00:01:57,316 --> 00:01:59,944
Tonight, all eyes
are on the moon

2
00:02:00,019 --> 00:02:03,079
as scientists
around the world
are piecing together

3
00:02:03,155 --> 00:02:06,522
the causes
of this unprecedented
lunar phenomenon.

4
00:02:06,592 --> 00:02:09,186
We're here on the campus
of Plymouth Institute
of T echnology

5
00:02:09,261 --> 00:02:13,220
to speak with
staff astrophysicist,
Dr. Lana Gale.

6
00:02:13,299 --> 00:02:15,563
Doctor, what
can you tell us?

7
00:02:15,634 --> 00:02:18,501
Well, basically,
we've been blindsided.

8
00:02:18,570 --> 00:02:22,597
The orbit of an undetected
asteroid has intersected
with the Moon's orbit

9
00:02:22,675 --> 00:02:24,506
and the two
have collided.

10
00:02:24,576 --> 00:02:26,976
While we would like
to think that we would see
something like this coming,

11
00:02:27,046 --> 00:02:29,537
the sky is a vast place,
and unfortunately,

12
00:02:29,615 --> 00:02:32,140
we don't have all
the resources that
we need to fully cover it.

13
00:02:32,217 --> 00:02:36,017
And what can you tell us
of what we're seeing
up there?

14
00:02:36,088 --> 00:02:37,919
What we're seeing
is an impact cloud

15
00:02:37,990 --> 00:02:40,424
of debris
and regolith that
will eventually subside.

16
00:02:40,492 --> 00:02:41,982
Regolith?

17
00:02:42,061 --> 00:02:44,495
The powdery rock covering
the lunar surface.

18
00:02:44,563 --> 00:02:47,532
So I guess
the more urgent
question would be

19
00:02:47,599 --> 00:02:49,430
is there
any cause
for alarm?

20
00:02:49,501 --> 00:02:51,264
These things are
always more alarming

21
00:02:51,337 --> 00:02:52,827
when they happen
so close to home

22
00:02:52,905 --> 00:02:55,032
but the best approach
is to wait and see
what happens.

23
00:02:55,107 --> 00:02:56,540
React to what develops.

24
00:02:56,608 --> 00:02:59,202
As my father used to say,
Dr. Lawrence Gale,

25
00:02:59,278 --> 00:03:02,338
"The universe is a case
of unfinished business. "

26
00:03:02,414 --> 00:03:04,609
Thank you very much
for your time, Dr. Gale.

27
00:03:04,683 --> 00:03:05,877
My pleasure.

28
00:03:05,951 --> 00:03:07,282
How was
it, Tony?

29
00:03:07,353 --> 00:03:09,378
You were awesome!

30
00:03:09,455 --> 00:03:12,720
You exuded confidence
and clarity
and strength,

31
00:03:12,791 --> 00:03:16,625
and knowledge,
and expertise,
and--but, regolith?

32
00:03:16,695 --> 00:03:18,253
That's what
it's called.

33
00:03:18,330 --> 00:03:19,820
I know that,

34
00:03:19,898 --> 00:03:23,061
but the average viewer
isn't that knowledgeable.

35
00:03:23,135 --> 00:03:25,933
Did you eat anything?
'Cause I kinda
skipped dinner.

36
00:03:26,005 --> 00:03:28,405
I'm sorry T ony,
please go home.

37
00:03:28,474 --> 00:03:30,271
I'll see you
in the morning.

38
00:03:30,342 --> 00:03:32,606
No. I'll pick us
up something;
we'll eat it here.

39
00:03:32,678 --> 00:03:37,638
We'll celebrate.
My treat. Tuna salad,
no mayo, heavy Dijon.

40
00:03:40,219 --> 00:03:41,481
Thank you.

41
00:04:45,918 --> 00:04:48,614
Dr. Bender.
Can you tell us

42
00:04:48,687 --> 00:04:52,123
whether the collision
on the moon poses
any danger here on earth?

43
00:04:52,191 --> 00:04:55,058
Well, for obvious reasons
it's premature to launch

44
00:04:55,127 --> 00:04:57,254
into any kind
of conjecture
at this time.

45
00:04:57,329 --> 00:05:01,197
What I can say is that
we at ASI are assuming
the leadership role

46
00:05:01,266 --> 00:05:05,202
in interpreting incoming data
gathered by the international
scientific community.

47
00:05:05,270 --> 00:05:09,138
ASI is the definitive space
agency in the world today,

48
00:05:09,208 --> 00:05:12,473
and we have our absolute
best people analyzing
this phenomenon.

49
00:05:12,544 --> 00:05:15,377
Very shortly we'll, uh,
we'll be presenting
our analysis

50
00:05:15,447 --> 00:05:18,473
to the White House,
where a press conference
will follow.

51
00:05:18,550 --> 00:05:20,381
One more question,

52
00:05:20,452 --> 00:05:22,682
what would happen
if a similar asteroid
were to hit the earth?

53
00:05:22,754 --> 00:05:25,279
Depending on speed
and trajectory,

54
00:05:25,357 --> 00:05:28,087
there would be
global repercussions.

55
00:05:30,696 --> 00:05:33,665
Garth? Dr. Lana Gale
is on line two for you.

56
00:05:33,732 --> 00:05:35,461
Yeah, I got
it. Thanks.

57
00:05:37,202 --> 00:05:39,102
Lana? Thanks
for calling.

58
00:05:39,171 --> 00:05:41,071
Have you seen
the latest?

59
00:05:41,140 --> 00:05:44,439
I'm probably not as up
to date as you are.
What's going on?

60
00:05:44,510 --> 00:05:48,412
Our information
on the halo
is a--concern.

61
00:05:48,480 --> 00:05:50,311
What kind
of a concern?

62
00:05:50,382 --> 00:05:52,850
Preliminary data shows
some of the asteroid fragments

63
00:05:52,918 --> 00:05:56,376
on a course
that will bring them
into earth's orbit.

64
00:06:02,461 --> 00:06:03,985
Hey, John.

65
00:06:04,062 --> 00:06:05,791
You weren't
on the Moon
last night, were you?

66
00:06:05,864 --> 00:06:09,231
Hey, John?
All that dust and
debris floating around,

67
00:06:09,301 --> 00:06:11,565
it kinda looks
like your handiwork.

68
00:06:11,637 --> 00:06:15,334
If I was up on the moon
last night doing my work?

69
00:06:15,407 --> 00:06:17,136
It wouldn't be
there anymore.

70
00:06:17,209 --> 00:06:19,234
Copy that.

71
00:06:19,311 --> 00:06:20,278
Checklist.

72
00:06:20,345 --> 00:06:21,334
Good to go?

73
00:06:21,413 --> 00:06:22,380
Yep.

74
00:06:22,447 --> 00:06:23,812
Let's blow
the building.

75
00:06:25,450 --> 00:06:27,145
All right, Ollie,
how we looking?

76
00:06:27,219 --> 00:06:29,585
Locked and
stocked, buddy.

77
00:06:29,655 --> 00:06:32,852
Check it out.

78
00:06:32,925 --> 00:06:35,052
Good. Right
on schedule.

79
00:06:35,127 --> 00:06:37,493
Looks like you're
gonna owe me
20 bucks, homie.

80
00:06:37,563 --> 00:06:38,461
I shake on that?

81
00:06:38,530 --> 00:06:39,997
Oh, yeah.

82
00:06:40,065 --> 00:06:41,726
Well, the building
ain't down yet.

83
00:06:47,239 --> 00:06:49,469
Oh my God.

84
00:06:49,541 --> 00:06:52,772
Abort right now.
Let's go. We gotta
stop the sequence.

85
00:06:57,349 --> 00:06:59,044
Bryna, shut it
down now.

86
00:07:02,154 --> 00:07:04,019
No, the system's
not responding.

87
00:07:04,089 --> 00:07:05,078
Ollie?

88
00:07:05,157 --> 00:07:06,818
I'm trying
to override it.

89
00:07:08,627 --> 00:07:10,595
Okay, let's
have some fun.

90
00:07:12,998 --> 00:07:14,295
What are
you doing?

91
00:07:14,366 --> 00:07:16,698
Bryna.
Continue to rebalance
the sequence.

92
00:07:16,768 --> 00:07:19,828
I'm gonna go
find that misfire.
Talk to me on the radio.

93
00:07:19,905 --> 00:07:21,372
You can't
go up there!

94
00:07:21,440 --> 00:07:23,931
We don't know how
that building's gonna
come down

95
00:07:24,009 --> 00:07:25,977
unless we rebalance
the system. Ollie?

96
00:07:26,044 --> 00:07:29,013
Figure out why that
clock is still ticking
and shut it down.

97
00:07:29,081 --> 00:07:30,139
I'm on it.

98
00:07:30,215 --> 00:07:31,204
I'll be back.

99
00:07:50,102 --> 00:07:53,538
Okay, Bryna, give me
the location of that misfire.

100
00:08:00,579 --> 00:08:02,342
Ninth floor.
8A.

101
00:08:02,414 --> 00:08:06,009
OK, copy that! Ollie?
Have you stopped
the countdown?

102
00:08:06,084 --> 00:08:09,178
John, the explosion
messed up
the whole system.

103
00:08:09,254 --> 00:08:10,846
It's lit up like
the Vegas strip.

104
00:08:10,922 --> 00:08:12,913
I'm tryin' to stop
the detonator but
it ain't happenin'.

105
00:08:12,991 --> 00:08:15,721
I know you've got
my back, Ollie.
So make it happen!

106
00:08:15,794 --> 00:08:20,959
Everything I'm seeing here
says that the charges did
not go off on their own.

107
00:08:21,033 --> 00:08:22,762
I think someone's
in there.

108
00:08:22,834 --> 00:08:25,598
Great. That's all we need.
Let's get the cops,
tell 'em what we got.

109
00:08:25,671 --> 00:08:29,163
If someone's still in there
who might keep
settin' things off,

110
00:08:29,241 --> 00:08:31,004
you won't have enough
time to fix it all.

111
00:08:31,076 --> 00:08:36,412
No! I'll have plenty of time.
Cause you're gonna fix
that damn clock!

112
00:08:41,086 --> 00:08:45,420
Hey! It stopped!

113
00:08:45,490 --> 00:08:46,957
How we doin'
for time?!

114
00:08:47,025 --> 00:08:49,926
There's no rush anymore.
The countdown stopped.

115
00:09:00,005 --> 00:09:03,099
What? No!

116
00:09:03,175 --> 00:09:05,735
That was the 5-minute warning.
That means that clock
is not off!

117
00:09:05,811 --> 00:09:08,780
I'm gonna have to reboot
the whole system.

118
00:09:08,847 --> 00:09:10,212
John, where
are you?

119
00:09:10,282 --> 00:09:13,547
I'm on the 9th floor now.
Do I go left or right?

120
00:09:15,787 --> 00:09:18,984
Left.
No, right!
My left, your right!

121
00:09:19,057 --> 00:09:21,753
Come on, Bryna.
Focus, okay?

122
00:09:21,827 --> 00:09:23,886
I'm coming up on
a large central room.

123
00:09:23,962 --> 00:09:26,362
In the middle
of that room,
you'll find column 8A.

124
00:09:26,431 --> 00:09:27,921
Hold on,
I think
I got it.

125
00:09:27,999 --> 00:09:30,399
That's the one
that's missing
its charge.

126
00:09:43,682 --> 00:09:45,274
C'mon, c'mon!

127
00:09:48,387 --> 00:09:49,979
Aaaah!

128
00:09:50,055 --> 00:09:51,488
Help!

129
00:09:51,556 --> 00:09:55,219
Hey, Joe?
Double-check lines
21A thru F.

130
00:09:55,293 --> 00:09:56,624
Okay.

131
00:09:56,695 --> 00:09:58,094
Are they
still hot?

132
00:09:58,163 --> 00:09:58,993
Yep, they're hot.

133
00:09:59,064 --> 00:10:00,361
Dammit.

134
00:10:00,432 --> 00:10:03,663
Help!
Help me!

135
00:10:03,735 --> 00:10:05,100
I'm coming!

136
00:10:12,077 --> 00:10:13,874
Okay!
Looks good!

137
00:10:13,945 --> 00:10:16,379
You're online and set
to go, now get
out of there!

138
00:10:16,448 --> 00:10:17,437
Hello?

139
00:10:19,050 --> 00:10:20,176
Help!

140
00:10:20,252 --> 00:10:21,947
We're gonna get
you out of here.

141
00:10:22,020 --> 00:10:25,979
I got a guy up here.
He's pinned down
by some debris.

142
00:10:26,057 --> 00:10:27,547
I gotta get him out.

143
00:10:27,626 --> 00:10:29,890
On three, I'm gonna
lift this up, pull
your leg out.

144
00:10:29,961 --> 00:10:31,485
One, two, three.

145
00:10:36,067 --> 00:10:38,160
Get out
of my house!

146
00:10:38,236 --> 00:10:40,830
Hold on!
Stop!

147
00:10:40,906 --> 00:10:42,066
This is
my house!

148
00:10:42,140 --> 00:10:43,732
I'm trying
to help you.

149
00:10:43,809 --> 00:10:45,299
Now listen to me.

150
00:10:45,377 --> 00:10:48,505
Your house is about
to get blown
to bits, understand?

151
00:10:48,580 --> 00:10:51,811
John, just get out
of there, please.

152
00:10:51,883 --> 00:10:54,010
I'll be down
in 90 seconds.

153
00:10:57,522 --> 00:10:58,546
Come on!

154
00:11:07,032 --> 00:11:08,659
Less than
a minute left!

155
00:11:08,733 --> 00:11:10,030
I've jacked the override
into your system.

156
00:11:10,101 --> 00:11:11,591
See if you can
get access.

157
00:11:17,442 --> 00:11:18,431
Watch out!

158
00:11:19,978 --> 00:11:22,572
Come on!
You almost got it.

159
00:11:22,647 --> 00:11:23,773
Go, go, go!

160
00:11:25,884 --> 00:11:26,851
Come on!

161
00:11:29,187 --> 00:11:31,348
John, you gotta get
outta there! Move it!

162
00:11:34,359 --> 00:11:35,758
John, move now!

163
00:11:35,827 --> 00:11:37,522
Go, go, go!

164
00:11:39,331 --> 00:11:40,628
Oh my God!

165
00:12:04,589 --> 00:12:06,750
We now have
three reported strikes

166
00:12:06,825 --> 00:12:09,885
of asteroid debris,
and they're not
ordinary meteors, Lana.

167
00:12:09,961 --> 00:12:11,519
We're missing something.

168
00:12:11,596 --> 00:12:14,292
Why are so many of them
surviving atmospheric entry?

169
00:12:14,366 --> 00:12:15,958
These objects
aren't that big.

170
00:12:16,034 --> 00:12:17,399
They should be
burning up.

171
00:12:17,469 --> 00:12:19,460
Then it's gotta be
the density.

172
00:12:19,538 --> 00:12:23,736
The mass of the asteroid
must have been much bigger
than we anticipated.

173
00:12:23,808 --> 00:12:25,571
But it makes sense.

174
00:12:25,644 --> 00:12:28,169
Because you were right
about the ecliptic plane.

175
00:12:28,246 --> 00:12:30,111
The lunar
orbit's shifted?

176
00:12:30,181 --> 00:12:32,513
The numbers indicate
a very gradual shift.

177
00:12:32,584 --> 00:12:34,176
And it could still
self-correct but

178
00:12:34,252 --> 00:12:35,981
there's already a rise
in the sea levels

179
00:12:36,054 --> 00:12:38,454
and the jet stream is taking
a complete nose dive south.

180
00:12:38,523 --> 00:12:41,117
Which means a big
weather change.

181
00:12:42,761 --> 00:12:46,356
Yeah, the kind
that triggers
an ice age.

182
00:12:46,431 --> 00:12:50,162
Okay, have we located
the point of impact?

183
00:12:50,235 --> 00:12:51,702
No, nothing
we can see.

184
00:12:51,770 --> 00:12:53,260
But we've got
satellites in motion.

185
00:12:53,338 --> 00:12:54,635
We should get
images soon.

186
00:12:54,706 --> 00:12:57,072
Hey, Will,
how long before
we get a look?

187
00:12:57,142 --> 00:12:59,133
The probes
are on their way.

188
00:12:59,210 --> 00:13:00,575
I'm in my
office now.

189
00:13:00,645 --> 00:13:02,237
Did you copy
Garth on this?

190
00:13:02,314 --> 00:13:05,283
You should have
a spectral image
coming through.

191
00:13:05,350 --> 00:13:06,817
Yeah, yeah,
I've got it.

192
00:13:06,885 --> 00:13:09,649
Get your folks
to work on
that dark section.

193
00:13:09,721 --> 00:13:12,622
We're having a hard time
seeing through the halo.

194
00:13:12,691 --> 00:13:14,124
No problem.
Hey, Will,

195
00:13:14,192 --> 00:13:16,285
take a look
at this area.
Get on that.

196
00:13:18,363 --> 00:13:21,696
I hope you're not
sugar-coating this
to the suits in DC.

197
00:13:21,766 --> 00:13:25,327
No, but that's why
I'd like you here.

198
00:13:25,403 --> 00:13:27,030
They're gonna want
solid answers.

199
00:13:27,105 --> 00:13:29,471
Which they'd rather
hear from someone else.

200
00:13:29,541 --> 00:13:32,169
Nobody's gunning
for you here, Lana.

201
00:13:32,243 --> 00:13:36,145
I was actually thinking
more of--knives.

202
00:13:36,214 --> 00:13:38,910
Can we set aside
the past?

203
00:13:38,984 --> 00:13:40,713
I need you.

204
00:13:40,785 --> 00:13:43,310
You'll run
interference for me?

205
00:13:43,388 --> 00:13:44,878
All I can.

206
00:13:46,691 --> 00:13:47,885
Okay.

207
00:13:47,959 --> 00:13:51,326
I owe you one.
I'll arrange a flight.

208
00:13:51,396 --> 00:13:53,660
See you soon, Lana.

209
00:13:56,034 --> 00:13:58,730
Remember when I said
I'd never go back to ASl?

210
00:13:58,803 --> 00:13:59,792
I lied.

211
00:14:02,040 --> 00:14:03,064
Wanna beer?

212
00:14:03,141 --> 00:14:05,200
Cheers!

213
00:14:05,276 --> 00:14:07,335
Hey, next time,

214
00:14:07,412 --> 00:14:10,609
try not to scare
the crap out of us.
That's all I'm sayin'.

215
00:14:10,682 --> 00:14:11,876
Copy that.

216
00:14:11,950 --> 00:14:14,748
So the deal with
the homeless guy was

217
00:14:14,819 --> 00:14:17,754
this was his home and
he was just trying
to defend it.

218
00:14:17,822 --> 00:14:20,086
So I guess
I can't blame him.

219
00:14:20,158 --> 00:14:22,285
You're lucky
you got outta there.
You know that?

220
00:14:22,360 --> 00:14:23,918
You almost died.

221
00:14:23,995 --> 00:14:26,964
Yeah, but I didn't.
And the building
came down perfectly.

222
00:14:27,032 --> 00:14:29,057
So, on to
the next one.

223
00:14:29,134 --> 00:14:31,466
On to the next?
John.

224
00:14:31,536 --> 00:14:34,437
You're not really
gonna bust my chops
right now, are ya?

225
00:14:34,506 --> 00:14:38,465
Seeing as you
almost got crushed,
now is a perfect time.

226
00:14:38,543 --> 00:14:41,103
You can't let
your work
own your life.

227
00:14:41,179 --> 00:14:42,942
And yours does.

228
00:14:43,014 --> 00:14:44,504
Come on,
take that vacation.

229
00:14:44,582 --> 00:14:46,072
We don't have
anything coming up.

230
00:14:46,151 --> 00:14:50,611
Well, actually,
we do have a demo
possibly in Florida.

231
00:14:50,689 --> 00:14:53,954
OK, that's it.
I'm outta here.

232
00:14:54,025 --> 00:14:57,552
Where you going?
Come on, don't go,
we're celebrating!

233
00:14:57,629 --> 00:15:00,826
Hey. I almost
died today.

234
00:15:02,133 --> 00:15:04,465
It's not funny
anymore, John.

235
00:15:04,536 --> 00:15:09,564
She died three years ago.
You need to take
some time off.

236
00:15:09,641 --> 00:15:11,632
Your wife's gone, John.

237
00:15:11,710 --> 00:15:14,270
She'd want you
to have a life
where things

238
00:15:14,345 --> 00:15:17,041
grow and thrive
and not just crumble.

239
00:15:19,584 --> 00:15:21,711
Don't do that
to yourself.

240
00:15:25,657 --> 00:15:26,351
G'nite.

241
00:15:30,395 --> 00:15:34,024
Hey.
Twenty bucks.

242
00:15:34,099 --> 00:15:35,657
Man, you gonna
hold me to that?

243
00:15:35,734 --> 00:15:37,998
Oh, yeah.
Cough it up.
Let's go.

244
00:15:38,069 --> 00:15:40,503
Buddy, buddy,
buddy.

245
00:15:40,572 --> 00:15:41,596
Don't give me
