725
00:44:15,518 --> 00:44:17,213
Aaaaaaahh!

726
00:44:22,692 --> 00:44:24,922
Come on, guys.
Pick it up.

727
00:44:26,729 --> 00:44:28,822
John?

728
00:44:28,898 --> 00:44:34,359
John, listen we have
two of our best
shuttle pilots,

729
00:44:34,437 --> 00:44:38,271
but...on this one,
we need
a mission specialist.

730
00:44:38,341 --> 00:44:40,241
That specialist
is you, John.

731
00:44:44,314 --> 00:44:46,908
You want me
to go on
the shuttle.

732
00:44:46,983 --> 00:44:50,544
I don't have
any training to go
to the moon. OK?

733
00:44:50,620 --> 00:44:52,212
We need you
up there.

734
00:44:52,288 --> 00:44:53,346
We only get--

735
00:44:53,423 --> 00:44:54,913
One chance,
I understand that.

736
00:44:54,991 --> 00:44:57,255
We can't force
you to go.

737
00:44:57,327 --> 00:44:59,761
You'll have
first hand visual.

738
00:44:59,829 --> 00:45:01,990
We'd feel
more comfortable
if it was you

739
00:45:02,065 --> 00:45:03,362
up there, pulling
the trigger.

740
00:45:15,278 --> 00:45:18,611
All nuclear
reactions have
a magnetic charge.

741
00:45:18,681 --> 00:45:22,310
It's that entirely destructive
element of the nuke
we're trying to avoid here.

742
00:45:22,385 --> 00:45:24,785
So, by using
the electromagnetic
pulse of the nukes

743
00:45:24,854 --> 00:45:26,583
to boost
the magnetic
charge of our MEG,

744
00:45:26,656 --> 00:45:28,089
we can create a force
powerful enough

745
00:45:28,157 --> 00:45:30,955
to recharge
the magnetic field
of the Rima fault.

746
00:45:31,027 --> 00:45:32,016
In theory.

747
00:45:32,095 --> 00:45:33,756
For how long?

748
00:45:33,830 --> 00:45:36,321
Long enough for
the moon's own gravity
to take over.

749
00:45:36,399 --> 00:45:38,697
I'm just giving it
a jump start--
in theory.

750
00:45:38,768 --> 00:45:40,633
I heard that
you were going to

751
00:45:40,703 --> 00:45:42,364
accompany the M EG
on board the shuttle.

752
00:45:47,410 --> 00:45:50,538
Well, with
the situation
being what it is,

753
00:45:50,613 --> 00:45:51,477
yeah, I'm in.

754
00:45:55,518 --> 00:45:56,780
Now listen Albert,

755
00:45:56,853 --> 00:45:58,115
this MEG charge,
it's gotta--

756
00:45:58,187 --> 00:45:59,711
MEG what?

757
00:46:04,060 --> 00:46:05,118
What's going on here?

758
00:46:05,194 --> 00:46:06,786
We're just
exploring options.

759
00:46:06,863 --> 00:46:09,388
Ah.
Exploring options.

760
00:46:09,465 --> 00:46:12,195
Well, we don't
need any options.

761
00:46:12,268 --> 00:46:14,896
The nukes are
on their way.

762
00:46:14,971 --> 00:46:16,438
And when they
get here,

763
00:46:16,506 --> 00:46:18,633
I don't want so much
as a spit polish
to go on them

764
00:46:18,708 --> 00:46:20,767
without my authorization.
Is that clear?

765
00:46:20,843 --> 00:46:22,572
Yes.

766
00:46:22,645 --> 00:46:23,771
Good.

767
00:46:40,430 --> 00:46:42,990
Some big seismic
numbers coming in.

768
00:46:43,066 --> 00:46:44,533
How big?

769
00:46:46,002 --> 00:46:48,266
That's a 40% jump
from the last one.

770
00:46:48,338 --> 00:46:49,999
Will? What's
our status?

771
00:46:50,073 --> 00:46:53,008
Launch site weather
is getting much worse.

772
00:46:54,143 --> 00:46:55,474
Garth. This
is insane.

773
00:46:55,545 --> 00:46:58,013
We can't go up
in this storm.
Nothing can.

774
00:46:58,081 --> 00:46:59,878
That's not an option
and you know it.

775
00:46:59,949 --> 00:47:03,282
Anyone you put up
in that shuttle is on
a one way trip to oblivion.

776
00:47:03,353 --> 00:47:05,981
We're all
facing oblivion!
Get used to the idea.

777
00:47:06,055 --> 00:47:09,684
If we lose power,
they'll be
flying blind,

778
00:47:09,759 --> 00:47:11,249
that's lF we get
off the pad.

779
00:47:11,327 --> 00:47:14,490
They will make
it off the pad.
There's no alternative.

780
00:47:14,564 --> 00:47:17,294
Now the time for caution
and second guesses,
that's long gone.

781
00:47:17,367 --> 00:47:20,200
This mission is a go.
Do you understand?

782
00:47:21,871 --> 00:47:23,395
Then push it up.

783
00:47:23,473 --> 00:47:25,668
Get them the hell
out of here before
it gets any worse.

784
00:47:25,742 --> 00:47:27,972
victor, you can't
still be convinced

785
00:47:28,044 --> 00:47:30,103
the nuclear warheads
are going to do
the job.

786
00:47:30,179 --> 00:47:32,477
The moon is doing exactly
what my father
said it would

787
00:47:32,548 --> 00:47:34,607
indicating he was right
about the iron core.

788
00:47:34,684 --> 00:47:37,414
You just go on like
the facts don't exist!

789
00:47:37,487 --> 00:47:39,819
There are billions
of lives at stake!

790
00:47:39,889 --> 00:47:43,689
We need to be rational.
And we need to be right.

791
00:47:45,828 --> 00:47:47,159
We're pushing
the launch up.

792
00:47:47,230 --> 00:47:48,993
Lift off is five
hours from now.

793
00:47:49,065 --> 00:47:51,829
The weather leaves
us no choice.

794
00:47:51,901 --> 00:47:53,869
John. I need
a moment.

795
00:47:55,405 --> 00:47:58,499
I just got some news
from Baltimore.

796
00:47:58,574 --> 00:48:01,304
Those buildings
have collapsed.

797
00:48:01,377 --> 00:48:03,937
What about my team
and Bryna?

798
00:48:04,013 --> 00:48:06,573
We don't know.
I mean, we could
try but--

799
00:48:07,417 --> 00:48:08,349
John!

800
00:48:11,821 --> 00:48:13,914
Tell me we have
a solid plan.

801
00:48:13,990 --> 00:48:16,754
Yes.
We do.

802
00:48:16,826 --> 00:48:19,090
We go
with the nukes.

803
00:48:24,200 --> 00:48:28,102
Mr. Stevens, we'll
need your authorization, Sir.

804
00:48:55,364 --> 00:49:00,700
It's getting
pretty bad
out there.

805
00:49:00,770 --> 00:49:02,761
If you want
to be alone,
I can wait.

806
00:49:02,839 --> 00:49:04,272
No, come in.

807
00:49:08,244 --> 00:49:09,836
I heard about
what happened.

808
00:49:09,912 --> 00:49:12,380
The buildings.
I'm sorry.

809
00:49:12,448 --> 00:49:16,407
Garth has some folks
trying to contact
city officials

810
00:49:16,486 --> 00:49:18,078
to locate
your colleagues.

811
00:49:21,624 --> 00:49:23,421
Is that her?

812
00:49:23,493 --> 00:49:25,393
No.

813
00:49:25,461 --> 00:49:26,894
That's my wife.

814
00:49:26,963 --> 00:49:29,557
She passed away
three years ago.

815
00:49:29,632 --> 00:49:33,227
So when you said earlier
that you'd lost
somebody special,

816
00:49:33,302 --> 00:49:35,793
I understood what
you were talkin' about.

817
00:49:38,374 --> 00:49:41,537
I'm just standing here
wondering if she was
still around

818
00:49:41,611 --> 00:49:44,045
would I still want
to do this.

819
00:49:44,113 --> 00:49:45,808
Would you?

820
00:49:49,452 --> 00:49:50,942
I think
you would.

821
00:49:54,023 --> 00:49:56,218
The storm just
hit tropical status.

822
00:49:56,292 --> 00:49:59,352
They're reporting
gusts of up to
75 miles per hour.

823
00:49:59,428 --> 00:50:01,453
I've gotta get you
up in the air, John.

824
00:50:02,365 --> 00:50:03,354
Let's go.

825
00:50:54,150 --> 00:50:57,142
Launch pad wind velocity
63 miles per hour

826
00:50:57,220 --> 00:51:00,018
from the southeast.
Doppler is showing gusts

827
00:51:00,089 --> 00:51:02,887
to 71 mph
at 30, 000 feet.

828
00:51:05,695 --> 00:51:08,459
Control? Payload
is secured.

829
00:51:08,531 --> 00:51:10,226
OK, Shuttle Perseus,

830
00:51:10,299 --> 00:51:12,893
we are at T minus
three to launch.

831
00:51:12,969 --> 00:51:14,732
Hope everyone's
comfortable.

832
00:51:14,804 --> 00:51:16,294
Comfortable?

833
00:51:16,372 --> 00:51:18,897
I'm strapped
onto the world 's
biggest vibrating whale

834
00:51:18,975 --> 00:51:20,408
about to blast
through a hurricane

835
00:51:20,476 --> 00:51:22,000
and this guy's
talking comfortable.

836
00:51:22,078 --> 00:51:22,908
Sorry, John?

837
00:51:22,979 --> 00:51:24,776
You can
hear me?

838
00:51:24,847 --> 00:51:27,475
Oh, yeah.
We're all
wired in.

839
00:51:27,550 --> 00:51:28,949
visual, too.

840
00:51:29,018 --> 00:51:32,283
OK. Sorry.
That's good
to know.

841
00:51:32,355 --> 00:51:34,482
Control, we've
got full green

842
00:51:34,557 --> 00:51:37,617
on O2 and Nitro,
tanks 1, 2, 3 and 4.
Please confirm.

843
00:51:37,693 --> 00:51:39,285
Confirmed, Captain.

844
00:51:39,362 --> 00:51:41,990
I'm handing over
full system access
to you now.

845
00:51:42,064 --> 00:51:47,366
T emperature is holding
steady on nuclear pulse
engines 1 and 2, confirm?

846
00:51:47,436 --> 00:51:51,668
Roger, Perseus.
Nuclear pulse engines
1 and 2 are solid.

847
00:51:51,741 --> 00:51:54,801
Nuclear pulse?
I thought they were
in the test phase.

848
00:51:54,877 --> 00:51:56,777
They are.

849
00:51:56,846 --> 00:51:58,871
You're joking,
right?

850
00:51:58,948 --> 00:52:01,508
You know a faster way
to get to the moon,
victor, I'm all ears.

851
00:52:01,584 --> 00:52:06,419
OK Perseus. Looking
for your readiness to
proceed with launch. Over?

852
00:52:06,489 --> 00:52:09,720
Roger control.
We are locked in,

853
00:52:09,792 --> 00:52:12,818
temperature's a go,
pressure's a go,

854
00:52:12,895 --> 00:52:16,922
Roger that.
T minus 2 minutes
to launch.

855
00:52:25,241 --> 00:52:28,438
Control, we've got
some flashing red
up here. Standing by.

856
00:52:29,612 --> 00:52:31,045
She's got a wind
sheer warning.

857
00:52:31,113 --> 00:52:32,637
Bypass it.

858
00:52:40,056 --> 00:52:41,614
OK flight directors,

859
00:52:41,691 --> 00:52:44,353
I want a go no go
for launch.
CapComm Perseus.

860
00:52:44,427 --> 00:52:46,224
Go launch.
Go for launch.

861
00:52:46,295 --> 00:52:47,091
Retro?

862
00:52:47,163 --> 00:52:47,959
Go launch.

863
00:52:48,030 --> 00:52:49,019
Trajectory?

864
00:52:49,098 --> 00:52:50,395
No go for flight.

865
00:52:50,466 --> 00:52:53,458
I've got a no go
signal for flight.

866
00:52:53,536 --> 00:52:55,367
Booster.

867
00:52:55,438 --> 00:53:00,137
No go, Flight Director.
Negative. I've got
a no go for launch.

868
00:53:00,209 --> 00:53:01,676
Oh, perfect.

869
00:53:01,744 --> 00:53:04,474
Four nuclear bombs, two
nuclear pulse engines

870
00:53:04,547 --> 00:53:06,139
aboard a no
go flight.

871
00:53:06,215 --> 00:53:08,046
T minus 1 minute
to launch.

872
00:53:12,154 --> 00:53:15,089
Navigation? Give me
your pre-flight status.

873
00:53:15,157 --> 00:53:21,494
Flight, navigation
is no go for launch.

874
00:53:21,564 --> 00:53:23,156
We have red lights
across the board.

875
00:53:23,232 --> 00:53:25,257
We cannot launch
this thing. We
must abort now.

876
00:53:25,334 --> 00:53:26,926
30 seconds
to launch.

877
00:53:27,003 --> 00:53:28,903
Don't.
It's not gonna get
any better out there.

878
00:53:28,971 --> 00:53:32,839
They're gonna be thrown
around like deck chairs.
I can't do this!

879
00:53:32,908 --> 00:53:36,344
Will, you listen to me.
I'd like to give you
70 degrees and sunshine

880
00:53:36,412 --> 00:53:38,744
so you could
launch properly.

881
00:53:38,814 --> 00:53:40,873
But I'm afraid that's
not gonna happen.

882
00:53:40,950 --> 00:53:43,578
Now don't you
turn that key.

883
00:53:43,652 --> 00:53:46,280
T minus 20 seconds
to launch.

884
00:53:54,530 --> 00:53:57,294
Ten, nine, eight,

885
00:53:57,366 --> 00:54:00,028
seven, six, five,

886
00:54:00,102 --> 00:54:01,831
four, three,

887
00:54:01,904 --> 00:54:04,429
two, one--

888
00:54:11,447 --> 00:54:13,915
We have main
engine ignition.

889
00:54:30,933 --> 00:54:32,924
Shuttle Perseus has
cleared the tower.

890
00:54:53,823 --> 00:54:55,552
We've got three
reds, Perseus.

891
00:54:55,624 --> 00:54:58,252
Roger control. We sustained
a lightning strike.

892
00:55:03,265 --> 00:55:05,256
Control, we are
losing trajectory.

893
00:55:05,334 --> 00:55:07,598
Raise secondary
thrust 20 percent.

894
00:55:07,670 --> 00:55:09,297
Copy that.

895
00:55:09,371 --> 00:55:11,305
Standing by.

896
00:55:24,587 --> 00:55:26,555
Control, we are
losing horizon.

897
00:55:26,622 --> 00:55:31,082
Storm wind velocity has
hit 87 miles per hour.

898
00:55:31,160 --> 00:55:32,855
Flight? They're
being blown
off course.

899
00:55:32,928 --> 00:55:35,658
Raise secondary
thrust 30 percent.

900
00:55:35,731 --> 00:55:37,289
Come on,
come on!

901
00:55:40,369 --> 00:55:41,631
Will, that's
not doin' it.

902
00:55:44,006 --> 00:55:46,304
Perseus, we're going
to change course

903
00:55:46,375 --> 00:55:48,673
heading to
straighten you out.
Adjust trajectory.

904
00:55:48,744 --> 00:55:51,679
30 degrees
north west
with the wind.

905
00:55:51,747 --> 00:55:54,307
Locking onto course.

906
00:55:56,152 --> 00:55:57,915
Come on!

907
00:56:04,493 --> 00:56:06,188
Stabilizing.

908
00:56:07,863 --> 00:56:10,593
Control, roll maneuver
is successful.

909
00:56:10,666 --> 00:56:12,691
We are back
on trajectory.

910
00:56:24,980 --> 00:56:27,540
Shuttle Perseus has
booster separation.

911
00:56:29,585 --> 00:56:31,280
Control, we
are hypersonic
and away.

912
00:56:33,088 --> 00:56:35,716
Ladies and gentlemen,
we have safe lift-off

913
00:56:35,791 --> 00:56:37,588
of Shuttle Perseus
lunar mission.

914
00:56:39,929 --> 00:56:41,453
Godspeed.

915
00:56:48,804 --> 00:56:50,237
You still with
us, John?

916
00:56:50,306 --> 00:56:52,638
Yeah, most
of me.

917
00:56:54,810 --> 00:56:57,142
With the risky launch
of the Shuttle Perseus

918
00:56:57,213 --> 00:57:01,047
from storm-battered Houston,
there is now hope
that the ASI shuttle crew

919
00:57:01,116 --> 00:57:03,983
can avert
the threat of disaster
approaching our planet.

920
00:57:04,053 --> 00:57:07,113
Today we are one planet
without borders
or differences.

921
00:57:07,189 --> 00:57:10,522
And every thought and prayer
is with the crew
of the Shuttle Perseus

922
00:57:10,593 --> 00:57:14,324
as they set out
to achieve what
some say is impossible.

923
00:57:18,901 --> 00:57:21,734
Well,

924
00:57:21,804 --> 00:57:24,864
I never thought I'd
hear myself say it but--

925
00:57:24,940 --> 00:57:27,807
that was better than
blowin' up a building.

926
00:57:34,883 --> 00:57:37,215
Control, we
are ready to
leave orbit.

927
00:57:37,286 --> 00:57:38,913
Roger Perseus.

928
00:57:38,988 --> 00:57:42,321
Proceed with
trans-lunar injection.
On your mark.

929
00:57:42,391 --> 00:57:43,915
Nuclear pulse
engines engaged.

930
00:57:45,060 --> 00:57:46,823
Nuclear pulse?

931
00:57:46,895 --> 00:57:49,796
For when 20,000 miles
per hour just ain't
fast enough.

932
00:57:53,402 --> 00:57:55,131
Hold on to
your hats.

933
00:58:08,484 --> 00:58:10,816
Control? We
have a problem.

934
00:58:10,886 --> 00:58:13,616
Advance radar
is tracking
incoming lunar debris

935
00:58:13,689 --> 00:58:15,281
and it's right on
our flight path.

936
00:58:15,357 --> 00:58:16,915
Roger Perseus.

937
00:58:16,992 --> 00:58:18,789
You are cleared
for evasive action.

938
00:58:18,861 --> 00:58:21,193
Repeat, you are cleared
for evasive action.

939
00:58:21,263 --> 00:58:23,993
Roger control,
we' re on the move.

940
00:58:58,834 --> 00:59:00,995
Control? Evasive
maneuvers successful.

941
00:59:01,070 --> 00:59:03,538
You'd better start
tracking those bogeys.

942
00:59:03,605 --> 00:59:05,937
By my calculations,
they're in
the Earth's gravity

943
00:59:06,008 --> 00:59:07,873
and heading
your way.

944
00:59:07,943 --> 00:59:10,605
And a couple of those rocks
looked bigger
than the Mexico meteor.

945
00:59:13,916 --> 00:59:16,749
Just in the last hour,
this storm has
really started

946
00:59:16,819 --> 00:59:20,220
to bear down on the city.
Power is reported being
lost in two-thirds

947
00:59:20,289 --> 00:59:24,089
of the homes and officials
are calling for a complete
and immediate evacuation

948
00:59:24,159 --> 00:59:27,595
evacuation of the entire
tri-county area.
But with similar storms

949
00:59:27,663 --> 00:59:30,154
storms ravaging
the entire coast
and the imminent mood

950
00:59:30,232 --> 00:59:33,793
can be striking
anywhere at any time,
the question remains:

951
00:59:33,869 --> 00:59:36,838
Evacuate to where?
For now, it appears

952
00:59:36,905 --> 00:59:38,998
there's no escape
from this earthstorm.

953
00:59:48,717 --> 00:59:50,548
What in the hell?

954
00:59:50,619 --> 00:59:53,179
Everybody, stay calm.
Stay calm!

955
00:59:53,255 --> 00:59:54,779
Go to generator power.

956
00:59:56,892 --> 00:59:59,019
That's gonna put us
on a bit of a clock.

957
00:59:59,094 --> 01:00:02,029
We got limited time
on the generators.

958
01:00:02,097 --> 01:00:05,464
If we can't get
the power back up,
we'll lose them completely.

959
01:00:05,534 --> 01:00:07,968
They need us
to fly home.

960
01:00:08,036 --> 01:00:11,267
Will? I need a precise
time estimate on our
remaining power.

961
01:00:11,340 --> 01:00:12,671
I'm workin' on it.

962
01:00:12,741 --> 01:00:13,708
Someone to
see you.

963
01:00:13,776 --> 01:00:15,107
What do you got?

964
01:00:15,177 --> 01:00:17,077
OK, call downstairs,
tell 'em to crank it up.

965
01:00:19,715 --> 01:00:24,084
I really need to see
my boss, John Redding.
It's very, very important.

966
01:00:24,153 --> 01:00:26,644
Bryna? I'm
Dr. Lana Gale.

967
01:00:26,722 --> 01:00:28,849
We are so glad
that you're OK.

968
01:00:28,924 --> 01:00:32,121
Thanks. I really need
to see John Redding.
It's urgent.

969
01:00:32,194 --> 01:00:33,786
Will you settle
for a video feed?

970
01:00:33,862 --> 01:00:35,386
John's on
the shuttle Perseus,

971
01:00:35,464 --> 01:00:38,900
a few thousand miles
from the moon.

972
01:00:38,967 --> 01:00:40,992
The moon?

973
01:00:45,307 --> 01:00:47,172
You can speak
to John right
over here.

974
01:00:50,045 --> 01:00:51,103
Oh my God.

975
01:00:52,815 --> 01:00:55,181
Will, pull up
a video feed
on John.

976
01:00:56,318 --> 01:00:58,445
Uh, John,
you there?

977
01:00:58,520 --> 01:01:01,080
Bryna, is
that you?

978
01:01:01,156 --> 01:01:02,248
Yeah.

979
01:01:02,324 --> 01:01:04,656
Oh, hey, can
you see me?

980
01:01:04,726 --> 01:01:06,557
Yeah, I can.

981
01:01:06,628 --> 01:01:08,528
Look, I know I said
you needed
to get away,

982
01:01:08,597 --> 01:01:10,087
but this is
a little ridiculous.

983
01:01:10,165 --> 01:01:12,565
Listen, thank God
you're alive.

984
01:01:12,634 --> 01:01:13,828
How's Oliver?

985
01:01:13,902 --> 01:01:15,426
Oh, he's fine,
he's fine,

986
01:01:15,504 --> 01:01:17,369
he's banged up
and in the hospital
but, uh,

987
01:01:17,439 --> 01:01:18,963
but he's gonna
be okay.

988
01:01:19,041 --> 01:01:21,703
John, you're
coming back, right?

989
01:01:21,777 --> 01:01:25,679
Oh, yeah. That is
most definitely
on this itinerary.

990
01:01:25,747 --> 01:01:29,513
Good, because I went
to hell and back to get
that thing you asked for.

991
01:01:29,585 --> 01:01:31,075
You got it?

992
01:01:31,153 --> 01:01:35,715
Great. Be sure you get
it to a woman named
Lana Gale.

993
01:01:35,791 --> 01:01:37,349
You be sure
you give it
to her.

994
01:01:37,426 --> 01:01:40,884
Yeah. She's
right here
next to me.

995
01:01:40,963 --> 01:01:42,328
You did great.

996
01:01:42,397 --> 01:01:44,262
If you can believe it,
they've got me

997
01:01:44,333 --> 01:01:46,858
overseeing a blast job
that's gonna save
the moon.

998
01:01:46,935 --> 01:01:50,496
Now you get
that sample to Lana,
and I'll see you around.

999
01:01:50,572 --> 01:01:51,937
Stay safe
down there.

1000
01:01:52,007 --> 01:01:54,475
Yeah.
Bye, John.

1001
01:02:00,983 --> 01:02:02,041
Where did you
get this?

1002
01:02:02,117 --> 01:02:05,712
A meteor crater
in Baltimore.

1003
01:02:10,325 --> 01:02:11,519
I'm in the lab!

1004
01:02:23,872 --> 01:02:25,840
Perseus is
on target.

1005
01:02:25,908 --> 01:02:28,433
Entering the outer phase
of the debris field.

1006
01:02:32,548 --> 01:02:35,915
Control, we're taking
evasive action.

1007
01:02:35,984 --> 01:02:38,885
Buckle up guys,
this could get
a bit rough.

1008
01:03:14,823 --> 01:03:15,619
What's that?

1009
01:03:15,691 --> 01:03:16,715
Restraint.

1010
01:03:16,792 --> 01:03:18,555
Something's wrong.

1011
01:03:18,627 --> 01:03:20,618
Something's wrong
with the nukes?

1012
01:03:20,696 --> 01:03:23,631
Yeah, I've got
to go and secure
the cargo hold.

1013
01:03:25,968 --> 01:03:28,232
Continuing multiple
targets on forward radar.

1014
01:03:40,882 --> 01:03:41,974
Ahhhh!

1015
01:03:42,818 --> 01:03:43,477
Ohhh!

1016
01:03:46,855 --> 01:03:48,686
What the hell
is that?

1017
01:03:48,757 --> 01:03:50,622
Flight, we've lost
communications feed

1018
01:03:50,692 --> 01:03:52,057
and secondary
hydraulics.

1019
01:03:52,127 --> 01:03:53,116
We've been hit.

1020
01:03:53,195 --> 01:03:54,423
How bad?

1021
01:03:54,496 --> 01:03:56,726
All directors
report your status.

1022
01:03:56,798 --> 01:03:58,595
Communications, get
us back online.

1023
01:03:58,667 --> 01:03:59,793
Ben, you
all right?

1024
01:04:02,838 --> 01:04:03,930
Ben!

1025
01:04:06,475 --> 01:04:08,170
Rachel, Ben's down.

1026
01:04:08,243 --> 01:04:09,642
What happened?

1027
01:04:10,912 --> 01:04:12,436
I think
he's unconscious.

1028
01:04:21,790 --> 01:04:23,724
Shuttle Perseus,
what's your status?

1029
01:04:23,792 --> 01:04:26,022
Control, we're clear
of the debris field
for now.

1030
01:04:26,094 --> 01:04:29,325
The shuttle
sustained a hit
and Ben's been hurt.

1031
01:04:29,398 --> 01:04:31,662
How about
the payload?

1032
01:04:31,733 --> 01:04:34,531
Got knocked
around a little bit.
John's with Ben now.

1033
01:04:34,603 --> 01:04:36,332
Just secure
that payload.

1034
01:04:36,405 --> 01:04:37,667
Forget about Ben.

1035
01:04:37,739 --> 01:04:39,468
John, do
you hear me?

1036
01:04:39,541 --> 01:04:44,274
Yes, I hear you.
Now could you
shut up, victor?

1037
01:04:44,346 --> 01:04:45,904
If that payload
gets damaged,

1038
01:04:45,981 --> 01:04:47,505
nothing else
is gonna matter.

1039
01:04:55,424 --> 01:04:57,119
I just hope Ben
doesn't have

1040
01:04:57,192 --> 01:04:58,318
a serious
neck injury.

1041
01:05:01,997 --> 01:05:06,934
I'm inspecting
the nukes now.
They seem to be OK.

1042
01:05:09,071 --> 01:05:10,936
Just a detached
cargo clip.

1043
01:05:14,609 --> 01:05:15,598
Payload secured.

1044
01:05:15,677 --> 01:05:17,440
Thank you.

1045
01:05:28,190 --> 01:05:29,555
Okay, how
much longer?

1046
01:05:29,624 --> 01:05:30,818
Hold on,
hold on.

1047
01:05:34,496 --> 01:05:36,487
That's interesting.

1048
01:05:36,565 --> 01:05:37,657
What?

1049
01:05:41,103 --> 01:05:42,070
That's interesting.

1050
01:05:42,137 --> 01:05:43,126
What?

1051
01:05:43,205 --> 01:05:45,332
I'm printing.

1052
01:05:51,446 --> 01:05:53,073
That's interesting,
right?

1053
01:06:01,690 --> 01:06:05,182
Control, we're approaching
the Rima Sursalis.

1054
01:06:05,260 --> 01:06:08,889
Our first clear view
of the fault should
be any minute now.

1055
01:06:20,275 --> 01:06:22,038
John!

1056
01:06:22,110 --> 01:06:23,737
Are you
seeing this?

1057
01:06:31,987 --> 01:06:33,545
Whoa.

1058
01:06:33,622 --> 01:06:36,648
Looks like we've
got our work cut
out for us.

1059
01:06:40,896 --> 01:06:43,330
My father was
right, victor.

1060
01:06:43,398 --> 01:06:46,299
The lunar core
is composed mainly
of dense metals.

1061
01:06:46,368 --> 01:06:48,996
It's not a fantasy
anymore. It's a fact.

1062
01:06:49,070 --> 01:06:53,234
It's full of uranium,
iron--the list
goes on.

1063
01:06:53,308 --> 01:06:56,038
And it's far
from the structure
of M iranda.

1064
01:06:56,111 --> 01:06:58,636
My father's theory
was just proven.

1065
01:06:58,713 --> 01:07:01,682
Correct me
if I'm wrong
but doesn't that mean

1066
01:07:01,750 --> 01:07:05,015
we should've sent
a MEG instead
of the nukes?

1067
01:07:17,599 --> 01:07:19,328
John?

1068
01:07:19,401 --> 01:07:21,062
John, are you
there? It's Albert.

1069
01:07:21,136 --> 01:07:23,104
That sample
that you sent
proves that the moon

1070
01:07:23,171 --> 01:07:26,038
has more iron in its structure
than we were planning
for in our blast.

1071
01:07:26,107 --> 01:07:29,201
Please tell me
that you guys are
kidding me right now.

1072
01:07:29,277 --> 01:07:31,711
I wish I was.
But we're working
on a solution.

1073
01:07:31,780 --> 01:07:35,716
Right. O K, you know
where to find us.

1074
01:07:35,784 --> 01:07:37,513
Rachel, we can't
use the nukes.

1075
01:07:37,586 --> 01:07:39,918
What?
Why?

1076
01:07:39,988 --> 01:07:42,183
The moon surface
is too rigid.

1077
01:07:42,257 --> 01:07:44,384
It wouldn't sustain
the shockwave.

1078
01:07:44,459 --> 01:07:46,586
Make the whole
situation worse.

1079
01:07:55,904 --> 01:07:59,271
John, come in.
This is Albert again.

1080
01:07:59,341 --> 01:08:00,535
Yeah.

1081
01:08:00,609 --> 01:08:01,974
We are gonna try
to convert the nukes

1082
01:08:02,043 --> 01:08:03,237
up there into
a M EG charge.

1083
01:08:03,311 --> 01:08:05,370
We almost have
it figured out.

1084
01:08:05,447 --> 01:08:07,210
John, you
still there?

1085
01:08:07,282 --> 01:08:09,944
John, I know it
sounds crazy

1086
01:08:10,018 --> 01:08:12,248
but we've been able
to assemble a puzzle
down here

1087
01:08:12,320 --> 01:08:14,117
using elements
of the shuttle
and the nukes

1088
01:08:14,189 --> 01:08:16,555
to come up
with a plan
that actually works.

1089
01:08:16,625 --> 01:08:18,422
I hear you Lana.

1090
01:08:18,493 --> 01:08:20,324
My only
question is

1091
01:08:20,395 --> 01:08:22,226
obviously we
can't put
a M EG charge

1092
01:08:22,297 --> 01:08:23,889
where we were
gonna blast.

1093
01:08:23,965 --> 01:08:27,196
OK, where do you
suggest we go?

1094
01:08:30,171 --> 01:08:32,139
Will, are
you on?

1095
01:08:32,207 --> 01:08:33,902
We're here, John.

1096
01:08:33,975 --> 01:08:36,034
See if you can
figure out for me

1097
01:08:36,111 --> 01:08:39,808
where the epicenter
of all this seismic activity
is within the fault.

1098
01:08:39,881 --> 01:08:42,782
Can you do that?
Kinda find out
where the fulcrum is.

1099
01:08:42,851 --> 01:08:46,412
Copy that, John.
I'll put the geology
team on it right away.

1100
01:08:46,488 --> 01:08:47,455
Did you
get all that?

1101
01:08:47,522 --> 01:08:48,819
Yep.

1102
01:08:48,890 --> 01:08:50,551
Good.

1103
01:08:50,625 --> 01:08:52,991
'Cause you're gonna
have to get us there.

1104
01:08:53,061 --> 01:08:56,656
Right. I'm on it.
Just be careful
in here.

1105
01:09:01,770 --> 01:09:03,897
This is Shuttle
Perseus to Control.

1106
01:09:03,972 --> 01:09:05,667
Standing by
for instructions.

1107
01:09:05,740 --> 01:09:09,141
Shuttle Perseus, you
are clear to maneuver.

1108
01:09:09,210 --> 01:09:11,906
Roger, control.
We're on the move.

1109
01:09:11,980 --> 01:09:14,710
All right, Albert,
what's the first step?
T alk to me.

1110
01:09:14,783 --> 01:09:17,479
OK, John, we need
a timing trigger.

1111
01:09:17,552 --> 01:09:21,613
There's a heating circuit
in your equipment that
you're not using right now.

1112
01:09:21,690 --> 01:09:22,987
Where?

1113
01:09:23,058 --> 01:09:26,118
Look for a bin
labeled MF431.

1114
01:09:26,194 --> 01:09:27,786
Look for
the orange label.

1115
01:09:30,031 --> 01:09:33,125
Orange MF431.
Got it. Go ahead.

1116
01:09:33,201 --> 01:09:38,605
You are gonna pull
out the igniter module.

1117
01:09:38,673 --> 01:09:41,039
And we can marry it
to the payload
circuit path.

1118
01:09:41,977 --> 01:09:43,239
Ahh!

1119
01:09:43,311 --> 01:09:45,939
If you see anything
green, don't touch it.

1120
01:09:46,014 --> 01:09:48,312
Can you confirm
that message
for me?

1121
01:09:48,383 --> 01:09:49,975
Nothing green.

1122
01:09:50,051 --> 01:09:53,043
Are you digging?
Did you find it?
It's clearly marked.

1123
01:09:58,126 --> 01:10:00,185
Right, got it.
Next?

1124
01:10:04,799 --> 01:10:08,735
John? Go to the circuit
boards towards
the flight deck.

1125
01:10:08,803 --> 01:10:11,033
You'll see a row
of black circuit panels.

1126
01:10:11,106 --> 01:10:12,368
Which one?

1127
01:10:12,440 --> 01:10:14,806
The one labeled
channel interface.

1128
01:10:18,713 --> 01:10:21,739
Behind that panel
you'll find the tubing
that you need.

1129
01:10:30,725 --> 01:10:33,091
They're cut.
Next.

1130
01:10:45,173 --> 01:10:47,164
Follow that cable
to the junction box.

1131
01:10:47,242 --> 01:10:49,176
Can I help you
find something?

1132
01:10:50,812 --> 01:10:54,509
Hey. Good to have
you back, buddy.

1133
01:10:54,582 --> 01:10:58,814
How can you maximize
the liquid hydrogen?

1134
01:11:02,123 --> 01:11:03,613
Will? Geology's
come up

1135
01:11:03,691 --> 01:11:05,420
with a new drop
point coordinates.

1136
01:11:05,493 --> 01:11:07,290
We're gonna have
to go straight
to the core.

1137
01:11:07,362 --> 01:11:10,923
We've calculated
a flight path down
through the fissure.

1138
01:11:13,301 --> 01:11:15,360
Got new coordinates
coming in for you,
Perseus.

1139
01:11:15,437 --> 01:11:17,735
We're taking you
down into
the fissure.

1140
01:11:20,642 --> 01:11:23,543
Roger, Control.
Coordinates received.

1141
01:11:23,611 --> 01:11:25,306
It's gonna be dark
down there.

1142
01:11:44,566 --> 01:11:47,694
Definitely the weirdest
bomb I ever built.

1143
01:12:07,589 --> 01:12:09,079
We've got
a problem.

1144
01:12:09,157 --> 01:12:10,556
What is it?

1145
01:12:10,625 --> 01:12:14,755
I've done
a recalculation
based on our solenoids.

1146
01:12:14,829 --> 01:12:17,059
Solenoids? What
about them?

1147
01:12:17,132 --> 01:12:19,896
The maximum power
you can expect to get
out of that contraption

1148
01:12:19,968 --> 01:12:21,595
about one hundredth
of what you need.

1149
01:12:21,669 --> 01:12:23,660
What?
No!

1150
01:12:23,738 --> 01:12:24,932
It's the velocity.

1151
01:12:25,006 --> 01:12:27,031
It won't give
you the pull
you need.

1152
01:12:27,108 --> 01:12:29,668
He's right.
It's not
gonna work.

1153
01:12:31,346 --> 01:12:34,804
We underestimated
the conduction
we got.

1154
01:12:46,928 --> 01:12:47,792
John!

1155
01:12:47,862 --> 01:12:49,090
Yes?

1156
01:12:49,164 --> 01:12:50,563
You better hold
on to something.

1157
01:13:33,541 --> 01:13:36,442
Control?
We're approaching
the new drop point.

1158
01:13:59,300 --> 01:14:01,268
Oh, this isn't
lookin' good.

1159
01:14:02,604 --> 01:14:03,935
John!

1160
01:14:04,005 --> 01:14:05,802
We've got increasing
seismic activity.

1161
01:14:05,873 --> 01:14:07,465
We've gotta get
out of here now

1162
01:14:07,542 --> 01:14:09,567
or we'll
get trapped.

1163
01:14:09,644 --> 01:14:12,112
Albert? Lana?
T alk to me guys.

1164
01:14:12,180 --> 01:14:16,310
John, listen.
I'm afraid I have
some bad news.

1165
01:14:16,384 --> 01:14:17,976
The M EG won't
work either.

1166
01:14:18,052 --> 01:14:19,781
The lines of force
are too small.

1167
01:14:19,854 --> 01:14:21,515
What do you mean,
too small?

1168
01:14:21,589 --> 01:14:23,853
I thought you guys
had this all figured out.

1169
01:14:23,925 --> 01:14:25,392
We've got to blow
this thing.

1170
01:14:25,460 --> 01:14:28,486
John, this
is Victor.
It won't work.

1171
01:14:28,563 --> 01:14:29,860
It's over.

1172
01:14:29,931 --> 01:14:32,559
It's not over.
What is the problem?

1173
01:14:32,634 --> 01:14:35,967
John, it's the magnitude
of force we
can't change.

1174
01:14:36,037 --> 01:14:38,767
The maximum field
we can create up there
with what we've got

1175
01:14:38,840 --> 01:14:40,774
is just not gonna
make a difference.

1176
01:14:40,842 --> 01:14:42,867
Lana? Come on.
We are up here.

1177
01:14:42,944 --> 01:14:44,935
Let's drop this sucker.
Maybe it will work.

1178
01:14:45,013 --> 01:14:48,210
He's right.
This is all we have,
we need to go.

1179
01:14:48,283 --> 01:14:50,649
No! There's gotta be
something we're
missing, Garth.

1180
01:14:50,718 --> 01:14:53,016
We have got
to make sure
the shot works.

1181
01:14:53,087 --> 01:14:55,749
Come on guys.
Help us out
up here, OK?

1182
01:14:55,823 --> 01:14:58,155
Think. What do we
have on board
this ship

1183
01:14:58,226 --> 01:15:00,160
that'll make
this thing work?

1184
01:15:00,228 --> 01:15:01,855
They just don't
have the power.

1185
01:15:01,929 --> 01:15:04,762
We're draining crucial
generator time.

1186
01:15:04,832 --> 01:15:06,299
We can't push
this any longer.

1187
01:15:06,367 --> 01:15:10,133
Wait a minute!
The engines.

1188
01:15:10,204 --> 01:15:12,138
They're sitting
on two nuclear
pulse engines!

1189
01:15:12,206 --> 01:15:16,142
The pulse engines!
Ben, we can get
access to those, right?

1190
01:15:16,210 --> 01:15:19,543
Is that an option, guys?
Can that be made
to work?

1191
01:15:20,915 --> 01:15:24,715
Albert? Lana?
Talk to me.

1192
01:15:24,786 --> 01:15:28,517
I think so.
Yeah, it's
definitely possible.

1193
01:15:33,695 --> 01:15:35,993
OK gang.
Here we go.

1194
01:15:38,566 --> 01:15:41,034
John, we have got
to get out
of here now!

1195
01:15:41,102 --> 01:15:43,570
The seismic activity
is increasing.

1196
01:15:43,638 --> 01:15:46,505
Copy that, Rachel.
We're almost there.
What do I do next, Ben?

1197
01:15:46,574 --> 01:15:48,633
The control panel
is above the engine.

1198
01:15:50,611 --> 01:15:54,206
The access code
is 8491 1 38.

1199
01:15:55,650 --> 01:15:57,618
1, 3, 8.
Got it.
Now what?

1200
01:15:57,685 --> 01:15:59,550
Now use the winch
to slide the MEG

1201
01:15:59,620 --> 01:16:02,088
inside the engine.
But please be careful.

1202
01:16:02,156 --> 01:16:04,090
Those engines are
extremely fragile.

1203
01:16:04,158 --> 01:16:06,149
But the two charges
need to be balanced,

1204
01:16:06,227 --> 01:16:07,489
and we don't know
that they are.

1205
01:16:07,562 --> 01:16:09,359
The line of force could
still be too weak.

1206
01:16:09,430 --> 01:16:11,455
But that's when
the moon's gravity
kicks in.

1207
01:16:11,532 --> 01:16:13,227
Please for once,
just trust me.

1208
01:16:17,238 --> 01:16:20,002
Fault index is
approaching the critical.

1209
01:16:22,643 --> 01:16:25,840
Oh dammit.

1210
01:16:28,483 --> 01:16:33,011
Everyone just listen up.
